df2 = pd.read_csv("data/coin_Cardano.csv")
df3 = pd.read_csv("data/coin_Dogecoin.csv")

About the columns:
Symbol - Refers to the abbreviation of the coin
Date - The time at which the certain row values pertain to. This is always at the end of day, as high's and low's are calculated after all ups and downs throughout the day
High - The peak value of the coin that day
Low - The bottom value of the coin that day
Close - Value of the coin after the market closes
Open - The value at which it started out the day (This can wary from the close value of the previous day)
Volume - The number of these crypto coins that are currently being moved
MarketCap - The number of these crypto coins that are currently availabled to be traded/purchased

#plt.plot(x1, y1, label = "Aave")

plt.legend()

As it can be seen the Iota coin seems to be plateauing its downfall. At the 19th day, it is evident that the coin may start to rise back up
The Cardano coin and Dogecoin appear to have a very linear form, thus can be said to be staying constant

df = df.head(500)
x = df[['Low', 'Open', 'Close', 'Volume', 'Marketcap']]
y = df['High']
for col in x.columns:
    plt.figure()
    plt.scatter(x[col], y)
    sns.regplot(x[col], y)
    plt.ylabel('High')
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.show()

The the line of best fit found on these models can be used to predict future HIGH data based on changing x values.
These trends that are found in these graphs can help traders find near linear relations that allow them to further predict the spiking or falling of values.
It also shows how some factors do not contributre much the value of the coin.

print("Suggested date to enter is 2020, October, 11-15")

date = str(input("Enter a date "))
times = int(input("How many days would you like to look ahead? "))

newdate = date + " 23:59:59"
df1111 = df1.loc[df1['Date']==newdate]
df0000 = df3.loc[df3['Date']==newdate]
df2222 = df2.loc[df2['Date']==newdate]

num = df0000.iloc[0, 4]
num1 = df1111.iloc[0, 4]
num2 = df2222.iloc[0, 4]
data = [num,num1,num2]
label = "Iota",'Cardano', 'Dogecoin'
colors1 = ['lightblue','lightsteelblue','silver']
move = (0.1, 0.11, 0)
plt.pie(data,labels=label,autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=15, shadow = True, colors=colors1, explode=move)

plt.title('Crypto High values for '+ date)
plt.axis('equal')
plt.show()

add = 1
for x in range(0,times-1):
    date1 = int(date[8])
    date1 = date1*10+int(date[9])
    date1+=add
    ndate = str(date[0:8]) + str(date1) + " 23:59:59"

    df3333 = df1.loc[df1['Date']==ndate]
    df4444 = df3.loc[df3['Date']==ndate]
    df5555 = df2.loc[df2['Date']==ndate]
    num3 = df3333.iloc[0, 4]
    num4 = df4444.iloc[0, 4]
    num5 = df5555.iloc[0, 4]
    colors3 = ['silver','gold','brown']
    data1 = [num3,num4,num5]
    plt.pie(data1,labels=label,autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=15, shadow = True, colors=colors3, explode=move)
    plt.title('Crypto High values for '+ ndate[0:10])
    plt.axis('equal')
    plt.show()
    add+=1

This half pie charts are used to repressent the values of the high's for each coin that has been specified. It helps to show how each coin chnages per day. It provides an easy to understand visual, that even new traders can use to anayslse.
